**Code Explanation:**

The script performs the core-tail decomposition and non-extensive metric analysis as requested: 1. Data Loading & Metadata Mapping: It loads the preprocessed trajectories and maps each dataset to its corresponding pure L vy-stable reference. It also extracts the tail index alpha from metadata.json if available, or falls back to theoretical values based on the mechanism. 2. Time Scaling & Normalization: For each dataset, it extracts the positions at four time points (t = [T/10, T/4, T/2, T]). It normalizes the positions by the time-dependent scaling factor t^(1/alpha). The reference L vy-stable datasets are similarly normalized. 3. KDE & KL Divergence: It estimates the empirical probability densities of the normalized positions using Kernel Density Estimation (KDE) with Scott's rule on a common grid that spans up to the 99.5th percentile to capture the tails. A small epsilon floor (1e-10) is added to avoid log(0) errors before computing the Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence using scipy.stats.entropy. 4. Sisyphus Metrics: For the Sisyphus cooling datasets, it calculates the Pearson kurtosis and fits the central peak to a Tsallis q-Gaussian distribution to extract the q-index, quantifying deviations from the Fractional Fokker-Planck (FFP) propagator. 5. Plotting & Saving: It generates log-scale plots of the normalized empirical PDFs overlaid with the pure L vy-stable references. It also creates summary plots of KL divergence vs. time, KL divergence vs. alpha, and Sisyphus metrics vs. time. All metrics and probability densities are saved to disk (.json and .npz formats), and a comprehensive summary is printed to the console for the researcher.

**Modifications:**

Added the required preamble, ensured all file paths use the data/ directory, removed subfolder creation, and wrapped execution in if __name__ == '__main__':. Fixed LaTeX strings to avoid escape sequence warnings.

